          "title": "Part VII",
          "content": "Part VII. Constantius was a ruler known for his gentle and compassionate nature, which made him strongly opposed to the unfair treatment of any group of people. He believed in kindness and justice, and this was reflected in how he treated those around him. Many of the officials in his palace were Christians, and he held them in high regard, appreciating their loyalty and good character. Despite his positive feelings towards them, Constantius faced a challenging situation. While he was in a lower position of power, known as Cæsar, he found it difficult to openly reject the harsh laws that had been established by the previous emperor, Diocletian. Additionally, he had to follow the orders of Maximian, who was in a higher position of authority. This meant that even though Constantius disagreed with the treatment of Christians, he could not always act as he wished. However, he did not let this stop him from trying to help. He worked to ease the suffering of Christians whenever he could, showing his empathy and willingness to protect them from the anger of the public and the strict laws that were in place. Constantius's actions demonstrated that even in difficult circumstances, one can strive to do what is right and stand up for those who are being treated unfairly. His legacy is a reminder of the importance of compassion and the courage it takes to support others, even when it is not easy to do so.\nContext recap: Part VII. Constantius was a ruler known for his gentle and compassionate nature, which made him strongly opposed to the unfair treatment of any group of people. He believed in kindness and justice, and this was reflected in how he treated those around him. Many of the officials in his palace were Christians, and he held them in high regard, appreciating their loyalty and good character.\nWhy this matters: Part VII helps learners in History connect ideas from The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
