          "id": "df-l06-c1",
          "title": "Part I",
          "content": "Part I: The Foundation of Constantinople. In this section, we will delve into the fascinating political system that was established by Emperor Constantine and his successors. We will also examine the military discipline that was enforced during this time, the impressive architecture of the palace, and the financial strategies that supported the vast Roman Empire. One of the last rivals to Constantine was Licinius, who ultimately became a captive and was part of Constantine's grand triumph. After a peaceful and successful reign, Constantine left behind a remarkable legacy for his family. This legacy included not only the expansive Roman Empire but also a new capital city, known as Constantinople, a fresh approach to governance, and a new religion that would significantly influence the future of the empire and its people. The changes initiated by Constantine were profound and have been recognized and honored by generations that followed. The era of Constantine and his sons was filled with many crucial events that shaped the course of history. It is essential for historians to carefully distinguish between these events, as they are interconnected by the timeline of history, yet each holds its own unique significance. By understanding these events and their context, we can gain a deeper appreciation for the complexities of this period and how it laid the groundwork for the future of the Roman Empire and beyond. As we explore these topics, we will uncover the rich tapestry of history that defines this remarkable time, filled with triumphs, challenges, and transformations that continue to resonate today.\nContext recap: Part I: The Foundation of Constantinople. In this section, we will delve into the fascinating political system that was established by Emperor Constantine and his successors. We will also examine the military discipline that was enforced during this time, the impressive architecture of the palace, and the financial strategies that supported the vast Roman Empire. One of the last rivals to Constantine was Licinius, who ultimately became a captive and was part of Constantine's grand triumph.\nWhy this matters: Part I helps learners in History connect ideas from The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
